Commentary.Commentary: So South Africa would look and hope to negotiate around 20 remaining overs of the day. India would be looking to cap off the day with a couple of wickets to make it another successful day of Test.

A gruesome day for the visitors. They were made to toil hard on Day 1. They would have hoped a new day could bring new hope but that was not to be. As on a hot and humid day their bowlers were made to work ultra hard and in the process they made some mistakes. Muthusamy should have had Kohli's wicket when the Indian skipper was on 208 but that was not to be as the spinner overstepped. Keshav Maharaj had a long spell but just a wicket to show for it. Muthusamy too picked up one in the end. Rabada was the standout bowler with three wickets.

The day belonged to one man - King Kohli! He was excellent from the start of the day and built on his start he got on Day 1. After Mayank Agarwal with his century and Pujara with his fifty set the platform. Kohli built on that with Rahane. First he continued, last night's good work with sides vice captain. Once Rahane got dismissed, the Indian skipper joined hands with Ravindra Jadeja. The duo added a massive 225-run stand with Kohli not just getting to his 100 but then going onto convert it into 250. Jadeja after taking his time, took the charge and fell just 9 short of a well deserved ton.
After dominating the day, India have finally declared. The tired South Africans will now have to come out and bat which won't be an easy task.

OUT! Jadeja holes out and with that India have decided to declare! And guess what? Muthusamy has not overstepped this time. Tossed up on middle, Jadeja looks to whack it over long off. He gets the height but not the distance. It goes to the right of long off, Theunis de Bruyn runs to his right and takes a very good catch. Jadeja misses out on a well-deserved ton but this shows the heart of this man. He could have taken his time to achieve the milestone but he decides to go for the big one and falls. Nonetheless, the man has played an innings worth being called as 'Sir'. India declare on  601/5.

Flatter outside off, Kohli looks to flat bat it through covers but this one comes off the lower half of his bat. Just a single.

The physio is out in the middle now. It looks like Keshav Maharaj has hurt his right shoulder in an attempt to save the run for his side. This just is adding insult to injury at the moment.

SIX! Jadeja now dances down the track and slams this one over the bowler's head for a flat maximum. Powerful hitting this!

FOUR! Short ball wide outside off, Jadeja rocks back in his crease and cuts it towards the cover-point region for a boundary.

FOUR! Now on the off side. Disastrous return for Maharaj. 21 runs of the over. Short outside off, Kohli cuts it with sheer venom and gets a boundary. That also takes Virat Kohli's international run count to 21,000. India have cut loose here and are in T20 mode now.

Short again, Kohli finds the fielder at mid-wicket with his pull.
SIX! Kohli too now takes the aerial route! Floated on off, Virat comes down the track and smashes it over long off for a biggie.

However, he has already shifted his body-weight towards the right side and cannot hold onto it. The ball races to the third man fence for a boundary.
Jadeja pushes this one towards point and takes a single.

Floated outside off, Jadeja lofts it inside out over the cover fielder for a single.
Short delivery outside off, Jadeja looks to cut it but is beaten by the bounce on it.

Kohli gets on the back foot and defends it. End of a very expensive over, 13 runs off it.
Jadeja opens the face of his bat and guides this one towards third man for a single.
Another shorter delivery outside off, Jadeja pushes this off the back foot towards covers for a couple. This brings up the 12th fifty for Ravindra Jadeja and he brings out his trademark celebration.
Jadeja cuts this shorter one outside off in front of point and gets a couple of runs.

FOUR! Short of a length delivery on off, Jadeja rocks back and pulls this one towards mid-wicket for a boundary.
Aiden Markram is back. 1-0-4-0, his figures so far.

Milked to long on for one.
In the air but safe. Flighted on off, Kohli looks to go over covers but gets no timing on it. Luckily it falls short of the man in the deep so just a single.
Floated on middle, Jadeja strokes it to long on for one.
On the pads, Kohli flicks it to the on side  and gets a single.
Short around off, Kohli looks to cut but gets a bottom edge which goes to the keeper on the bounce.

No ball! What has Muthusamy done here! It looked to everyone like he had got the wicket of Virat Kohli twice in two Tests but MUTHUSAMY HAS OVERSTEPPED! This is criminal from him, especially being a spinner. The ball is floated just outside off, Kohli prods forward and looks to defend but edges it. Faf du Plessis at first slip takes a very good low catch. Kohli starts walking off the pitch but the umpire wants to check the No Ball and he stops Kohli. He goes to the third umpire and the replays show that Muthusamy has indeed overstepped.
Kohli opens the face of his bat and guides it towards third man.
No ball! Muthusamy oversteps! The batsman has played that off the front foot and into the ground.
SIX! Bad ball and taken full toll off it! Short of a length ball on middle and leg, Kohli rocks back and slams this one over mid-wicket for a biggie!
Short delivery outside off, Jadeja cuts this one towards cover-point for a single.
Floated on off, pushed back to the bowler.
Another single which is milked down to long on.

Flicked to the on side for a single.

DOUBLE HUNDRED FOR VIRAT KOHLI! His 7th Test double ton. This man is just pure class. All the adjectives in the world is just not enough to describe this man. On the pads, Kohli turns it behind square on the leg side and gets a couple to get to his double hundred. He raises his bat with a huge smile on his face. His teammates and the crowd stand up to applaud the King! The King is back! This has not been his best year in Test according to his 'out of the world' standards but boy doesn't he make his bat do all the talking?

We are back for the final session of the day. Indian skipper, Virat Kohli walks out with Ravindra Jadeja to resume their innings. The skipper who is on 194 will be on strike. Senuran Muthusamy to bowl the first over of the final session.
... Day 2, Evening session ...

India have strolled through yet another session and out of the 5 sessions played in this match, they have dominated all 5. Kohli is just 6 runs short off his double ton and the next session will be all about on what total do India want to declare their innings because quite honestly, it does not seem like South Africa will be able to take 6 more wickets. South Africa look down and out and will just be waiting when do India declare. Only the wicket of Rahane fell in this session but except for that, nothing good happened for the visitors. Stay tuned for the final session on Day 2 which resumes at 1430 Local (0900 GMT).

117 runs in 28 overs for the hosts. Just 1 wicket of Rahane for the visitors. There seems to be no light at the end of the tunnel for the visitors here as India are on their race cars speeding away from them.

Drinks Break. Though South Africa got a wicket in the first hour of play after Lunch, it is India who are well and truly on top. It is a warm day and the frustration has started to show on the Proteas players' body language. They though will need to stay positive and find some ways to get the Indian wickets rather than waiting for India to declare.
Flighted on off, Kohli strokes it to mid off.

It goes to the right of Faf du Plessis at first slip. He is late to react once again and the ball races away to the fence. Things starting to happen for the left-arm spinner. Subdued celebration from the Indian skipper. Looks like he is eyeing a double ton.

Flighted on off, Kohli pushes it to cover.
Length delivery on off, Kohli pushes it off his back foot and takes a single.
Oh! Length ball outside off, it comes back in. Kohli has a poke at it but gets beaten.
Fuller on off, Kohli this time just eases it to cover.

Outside off on a length, Kohli leaves it alone.
Back of a length ball on off, Kohli pulls it wide of short mid-wicket and gets a couple as Vernon Philander cleans it up coming from mid on.
On off, Kohli nudges it towards cover and keeps the strike.

Poor from Vernon Philander. Flighted on middle, Kohli whips it to the right of mid on. Vernon Philander at mid on moves to that side but misfields allowing them to get two runs. Tiredness starting to show in South Africa's fielding now.
Flighted outside off, Virat drives it but straight to cover.
Tossed up on off, Virat plants his front foot forward and blocks it.
Floated on off, Kohli plays it late towards short third man.
Excellent running! Shorter on off, Kohli turns it behind square on the leg side and looks for two straightaway. Jadeja is quick too and they get it with ease.

This has been a tough tour for Keshav Maharaj but this might act as a sweetener as Rahane becomes his 100th Test  victim.

The South African players, after a tiring Day 1, walk out onto the field again. They are followed by Virat Kohli and Ajinkya Rahane, the Indian captain and vice captain respectively. Kagiso Rabada to continue his over that he had left incomplete yesterday with Ajinkya Rahane on strike.

Kagiso Rabada is down with South African great Shaun Pollock for an interview. Rabada says that there was a tinge of green on the surface and it was a decent Test wicket. Feels that they were a bit unlucky but states that it is how Test cricket works. He quips that that this wicket is a bit similar to the ones in Mumbai. Looking on the positives on Day 1, Rabada says that they bowled well and restricted the run rate a bit. Feels that had luck been on their side, they could have had some more wickets and gone back in with a smile on their faces.

Pitch report - Murali Kartik is down with Sunil Gavaskar for the pitch report. Kartik states that some rough areas started to form on the pitch after just 10 overs of play on Day 1. Mr. Gavaskar states that the pitch has dried up today and that is why it will play much better today for the batters. Adds that yesterday there was some moisture due to the rain and that helped the bowlers. Gavaskar thinks that with the second new ball in hand now, they should be looking to hit the perfect lines and lengths to trouble the batters. Further suggests that the South African bowlers should be looking to bowl in the area of uncertainty and mix it up with the short ball. The South African bowlers need to tighten up and not bowl loose deliveries.

On Day 1, South Africa started well as they kept the explosive pair of Mayank Agarwal and Rohit Sharma at bay, which resulted in Rohit Sharma being dismissed cheaply. However, from there on in, it was India all along. Mayank Agarwal was the star of the day as he got to his ton. Pujara and Kohli both got to their half tons with the latter still unbeaten. Rahane is with his skipper at the crease and both have combined for an unbeaten 75-run stand. India will be looking to continue their strong performance on Day 2 and as stated by Mayank Agarwal yesterday, they will be looking to post a total around the 500-run mark. As for the South African bowlers, Kagiso Rabada was the only successful bowler as he took all the wickets yesterday.

Welcome to the coverage of the second day of the Test match between India and South Africa. Will India continue to dominate the proceedings and outbat the visitors on Day 2? Or do South Africa have the bowling prowess to enforce a collapse? Stay tuned to find out!

So the day belonged to India but there were some positives for the South Africans as well. Will South Africa find a way to restrict India under 400 or will India continue to pile on the South African misery? Join us on 11th October, i.e., Friday for Day 2 of this Freedom Trophy. Till then, cheers!

Centurion from the day, Mayank Agarwal is caught down for a chat with Harsha Bhogle. Agarwal says he is very happy to get back-to-back hundreds. Tells he is happy as the team is in a good position having lost just 3 wickets. Mayank says he was happy with how he was playing today. Mayank says that long distance running and meditation has helped him to play big innings. Adds that reading his own game has also played its part. Tells there was moisture in the wicket and credits Rabada and Philander for the lines and lengths they bowled. On what will be a good score, Mayank says 450-500 will be good if they don't want to bat again.

It was a gruesome and tiring day for the South African bowlers. They started off well but were not consistent with their line and length. They were on and off throughout the day. Kagiso Rabada did not start well but at the end of the day, he was the only successful bowler as he got all 3 wickets. Nortje was impressive with his pace on debut but struggled for consistency. Philander bowled well but had nothing to show for it. Faf du Plessis would be looking for a better showing on Day 2 from his bowlers.

Pujara though fell against the run of play. Kohli replaced him out in the middle and played second fiddle to Mayank who got his second century of the series. Unlike the first innings of the first Test, he could not convert this into a double ton and fell prey to Rabada. Rahane and Kohli then took their time. The captain and vice-captain of the side then added an unbeaten 75 before bad light ended play.

A day that clearly belonged to India. After winning the toss and opting to bat, the hosts did not get off to a good start. Losing the Man of the Match from the previous game early on, it looked like on a green wicket South Africa would make the hosts pay. But Pujara and Mayank Agarwal had other ideas. The duo added a 138-run stand for the second wicket and solidified the innings with both the batters getting to their respective fifties.

FOUR! Part-timer gets a harsh welcome. Elgar starts with a drag down around off. Kohli's eyes lit up looking at that. He pulls it with sheer power through mid-wicket for a boundary.
Part-timer Dean Elgar to have a go now.
Ajinkya stays on the back foot and lets the ball pass to the keeper.
Floated outside off, Rahane blocks it to point.
Stays in his crease and defends the ball.
No ball! He covered the line of the ball and defended it. Muthusamy overstepped for the second time.
FOUR! Short ball outside off, Rahane looks to cut it but he doesn't middle it. It runs away to the third man fence for a boundary.
Rahane stays on the back foot and waits for the ball to turn. He blocks it in the end.
Floated on middle and off, Kohli drives it to long off for a single.
Floated on off, Kohli milks it to cover and keeps the strike.
FOUR! Brilliant shot! Floated on middle and off, Kohli whips it through mid-wicket. Bavuma gives it a chase and puts a desperate dive to save it but he comes second in the race.
Flighted on off, Kohli keeps it out.
Flighted on off, Kohli drives it on the up but straight to the man at cover.
FOUR! Short, wide and punished. Maharaj bowls it short outside off, Kohli gets on his back foot and cuts it through point for a boundary.
Floated on the stumps, Kohli defends it off the front foot.
Floats it in on middle and leg, Rahane drives it to mid on.
Another front foot defense by Rahane.
Goes on the back foot and guides the ball towards gully.
No ball! Flighted outside off, Rahane defends it to covers off the front foot.
Rahane comes on the front foot and defends it.
Pulls the length back a bit and it's slower though the air. Kohli off the back foot works it to the on side for a single.
Tossed up outside off, Kohli strides out and defends.
Loopy ball on middle, AR defends it to get through the over.
On the stumps and once again Rahane blocks it.
Flighted on the stumps, Rahane shows his composure and blocks it.
Darted around the pads, Kohli turns it to square leg for one.
Tossed up on off, Virat pushes it back to the left of the bowler.
Shorter on off, Kohli punches it towards backward point. Kohli looks for a risky single but Rahane rightfully sends him back.
Slightly quicker on off and middle, Rahane looks to defend but does so off the inner half of his bat.
Another calm front foot defense from Rahane.
Tossed up on off, Virat strokes it towards long off and gets an easy single.
Tossed up on off, Virat blocks it off the front foot.
Beauty! Muthusamy gives this air on off, it spins away after pitching. Kohli looks to defend but gets squared up.
Flighted on off, Kohli pushes it to cover.
Senuran Muthusamy is back on. Just 2 overs for him today so far. Went for 13 runs in those.

Drinks Break! India have had another successful hour today but South Africa will be happy seeing the back of the well-set Mayank Agarwal. After that wicket, they have managed to keep the run flow at bay but they will hope to take another couple of wickets before the end of the day. Virat Kohli and Ajinkya Rahane are out in the middle. They are taking their time and would look to get their eyes in before taking any risks.
Floated on off, Rahane defends it to get through another over.
Gives this air on middle, Ajinkya defends it to the on side.
Defended off the front foot by the batsman presenting the full face of the bat.
Shorter on off, Rahane punches it to the man at cover.
On the stumps, AR blocks it off.
Flighted on off, Rahane keeps it out.
Fuller on off, Kohli looks to drive but only gets a bottome edge.
Bouncer! Kohli ducks under it.
On the fourth stump line, Virat leaves it alone.
Length delivery outside off, Virat drives it towards mid off.
Good length ball on off, Kohli defends it off the front foot.
The batsman shows the full face of the bat and defends the ball off the back foot.
Shorter on off, Rahane cuts it to the man at point.
On off, AR is in no hurry and defends it with ease.
Gives this one air on middle, Ajinkya defends it with calmness.
Tossed up on off, Ajinkya defends it off the front foot.
Drifts one on middle and leg, Rahane looks to flick but the ball takes the leading edge towards backward point.
Floated on middle and off, Rahane keeps it out.
Another short ball, Rahane looks to pull but gets a bottom edge towards mid on. A quick single taken.
On the pads yet again Rahane stands tall to clip it to mid on. No run.
FOUR! Full on middle and leg again Rahane wristily flicks the ball to the mid-wicket boundary.
On the pads of Kohli, clips it to mid-wicket for a single.
Kohli tries to turn the ball to the on side but it goes off the leading edge of his bat.
FOUR! Pulled with power. Back of a length ball on off, Kohli gets on his back foot and pulls it with venom through mid-wicket for a boundary.
The batsman drives this through the covers.
On the stumps, Rahane keeps it out.
Floated on off, Rahane strokes it to point.
Tossed up on off, Ajinkya defends it off the front foot.
Tossed up on off, Ajinkya looks to defend but gets an inside edge onto the pads.
Floated on off, Rahane keeps it out off the inner half of his bat to the leg side.
Full ball outside off, Kohli plays it to point.
Kohli shows the full face of the bat and defends the ball off the back foot.
Shortish ball, defended off the back foot.

FOUR! A lucky escape for Kohli.  Short and fast delivery angled into Kohli, it gets too high on him after bouncing. He went for a pull but the ball went off the the gloves just wide of de Kock to the fine leg fence.
Again blocks the short ball off the back foot to the off side.
Short ball around off, Kohli goes on his toes to defend the ball.
Anrich Nortje replaces Kagiso Rabada. 10-2-46-0, his figures so far.
The batsman has played that off the front foot and into the ground.
Gives this air around off, Rahane keeps it out.

FOUR OVERTHROWS! School boy stuff from Rabada. Completely unnecessary. Flighted on off, Virat nudges it wide of point and takes a single. Rabada gets to the ball and sends a wild throw, way wide of the keeper. The batters don't even bother running the second because there is no backup and are completely sure that it will go to the fence.
Tossed up on the stumps, Virat calmly blocks it.
On the pads, Kohli turns it to square leg.
Floated on the stumps, Kohli strokes it back to the bowler.
Fullish ball on off, Rahane works it to point.
On a good length on off, Rahane gets properly behind the line of the ball and plays it to mid off.
Short ball on middle and leg, Kohli pulls and sets off for a single. He checks his run as Rabada is blocking his way. May be to avoid yet another fine! 200 comes up for India.
The batsman defends it from within the crease.
Kohli stays on the back foot and plays the ball to gully.
Good length ball, outside off, it swings in after pitching, de Kock collects.
Floated on off, Kohli strokes it towards point and keeps the strike.
Pushed to the cover region by the batsman.
On the pads, Kohli flicks it to square leg.
Floated on off, Kohli pushes it to cover.
On stumps, defended.
Floated on the stumps, Kohli keeps it out.
Short ball around off, Rahane was about to pull the ball but he misses the shot. The ball his the grill of his helmet. Umpire Chris Gaffaney calls out to the Indian team physio to check on Rahane.
Outside off, Rahane pushes the ball to the covers.
On the pads, Rahane clips it to the on side.
Full ball outside off, swings in and  de Kock collects it to his left.
Back of a length ball outside off, Rahane gets on top of the bounce and keeps it down.
Bouncer outside off, Rahane sways away from it.
Another one full and floated outside off, Kohli pushes this one towards cover.
Floated outside off, pushed towards the off side.
On the pads again, pushed towards the man at short mid on.
On the pads, tucked towards the leg side.
Flatter outside off, left alone by Virat Kohli.
Floated outside off, pushed towards cover.
Ajinkya Rahane, the vice captain of India walks out to partner the skipper in the middle.

OUT! The centurion has been dismissed by none other than the sole wicket-taker of the day, Kagiso Rabada! It was a good length ball, which was angled into Agarwal, it pitched and straightened a bit. Mayank had committed to the shot and the ball went off the outside edge to first slip. Just like his last wicket, the skipper of South Africa, Faf du Plessis at first slip takes a good catch. Mayank Agarwal walks off the pitch to a standing ovation from the crowd and the players. A great knock by him comes to an end.
Plays the ball on the front foot to the cover region.
Good length ball outside off, comes in a tad, Agarwal safely lets it go to the keeper.
Agarwal shows the full face of the bat and defends the ball off the back foot.
Short outside off, Agarwal camps on the back foot and plays the ball late to deep point for a couple.
Back of a length ball on off, Agarwal is firmly behind it to defend it.
Kagiso Rabada is back. He replaces Vernon Philander. 13-1-39-2, his figures so far.
Short and on the pads, Kohli whips it to the man at mid-wicket.
On the pads, Virat flicks it to square leg.
Tossed up on the stumps, Kohli blocks it.
FOUR! Nobody moves. Maharaj gets his length wrong as he drags it short and wide outside off. Kohli gets on his back foot and slashes it through point for a boundary.
On the stumps, Kohli defends it with confidence.
Gives this one air around off, Mayank looks to defend but it goes off the outer half of his bat wide of first slip for one.
On a good length, Philander get the ball to come back in with the angle. Kohli on his front foot to defend the ball, works it from the inside half of the bat to mid on.
Good length ball outside off, left alone.
Goes on the back foot to not such a short ball to punch it to short cover.
Good length outside off again, Kohli comes far forward on the front foot to play it to the covers.
Fuller on on off, Kohli cover the line to block the ball.
On a good length outside off, Kohli comes forward to defend the ball.
Defended off the front foot by the batsman presenting the full face of the bat.
Flights one on off, MA pushes it to cover.
On the stumps, Mayank keeps it out.

Has Maharaj dropped Kohli here? Oh yes, he has. Tough chance but certainly a chance. Slower through the air on off, Kohli hits it hard and straight. But he also hits it uppishly straight back towards the bowler. Keshav gets down to his left and gets his fingertips to it. Unfortunately for him he cannot hold onto it. The ball goes behind to long off and the batsmen take a single.
Tossed up on off, Virat defends it off the front foot.
Floated on off, Agarwal strokes it towards point for one.
Good length ball, angling into Kohli, who looks to drive but it goes off the inside half of the bat to mid on.
Plays the ball towards deep cover for a single.

CENTURY FOR MAYANK AGARWAL! This has been an excellent knock from the young batter. 200 in the first innings of the first Test and another century here. He has made that opening slot his. Good length ball outside off, Mayank looks to cut but it goes off the outer half of his bat wide of the man at gully. The fielder there dives but cannot get close to the ball and it races away to the fence. He fist pumps the air in delight. He removes his helmet and has a big, joyful hug with his skipper. Take a bow, young man!
Angled too far across, Agarwal lets it pass to de Kock down the leg side.
Angled into the batsman, Kohli woks it to square leg for a single. Agarwal on strike, he is on 99.
Full outside off, Kohli comes on the front and blocks it towards mid off.
SIX! Make that two in a row. Agarwal just one short of a well-deserved ton. Floated on off and middle, Agarwal comes down the track and smashes it over the bowler's head for another biggie.

SIX! This one is out of here. Flighted on off, Mayank comes down the track and smashes it over long off for a maximum. Gets into the 90s with that. Six to get into the 90s, well this is Sehwag-esque from the young Karnataka batter.
Shorter on off, Agarwal punches it to cover.
Good shot but also brilliant stop from Muthusamy. Floated on middle and leg, Virat drives it wide of mid on. Senuran Muthusamy runs to his right and saves a certain boundary with a dive.
Flighted on the stumps, Virat lunges forward and defends it.
On off, Kohli defends it off the front foot.
Good length ball on off, Mayank drives it to mid off. No run.
Floated on off, MA covers the line of the ball and pokes it to the off side.
Back of a length, generates extra bounce, Agarwal off the back foot plays it to the off side.
On off again, Agarwal plays off his front foot towards mid off.
Plays the ball straight to the cover fielder.
Good length ball on off, Agarwal comes on the front foot and blocks it to the cover region.
Vernon Philander is back on. 11-3-13-0, his figures. He has not got a wicket so far but he has been impressive.
Tossed up on middle, VK defends it to get through the first over after the break unharmed.
Tossed up on off, Virat keeps it out.
Shorter on off, Kohli defends it off the back foot.
Short outside off, Mayank cuts it towards point and rotates the strike.
The Indian skipper is off the mark. On the pads, Virat glances it towards square leg and gets to the other end.
Beauty to start with! Flighted outside off, Virat looks to defend but the ball spins away beating Kohli all ends up.

We are back for the last session of the day. It has gone a bit dark here but let's hope that there is no rain interruption. The South African players are all set to take the field. Mayank Agarwal walks out with his skipper, Virat Kohli to resume their innings. Keshav Maharaj to bowl the first over of the session.
... Day 1, Final session ...

The session belong vastly to the duo of Agarwal and Pujara. The duo continued on their impressive batting display from the first session and added a total of 138-runs with both the batters getting to their respective fifties in this session. It looked like India would end the session without any casualty but just about 10 minutes before the break Rabada found a way to get past Pujara. It was a tough session for the visitors but towards the end it looked like they found their energy back which was lacking prior. With one new batsman at the crease, South Africa will be looking to build on it and get on top in this Test. The question is can they? Join us after the break for the final session of the first day.
Tea! India's session but South Africa got into the groove right at the tail end.
Fuller on off, MA pushes it to cover and that will Tea on Day 1.
Length delivery on off, Mayank keeps it out.

The second slip in place now. Rabada signalled after the edge from Mayank Agarwal to his skipper that he wanted a second slip and now Faf obliges after having a chat with his partner, Quinton de Kock.

EDGED AND FOUR! Rabada is finding his steam back. Hits the deck hard on off and middle and makes the ball shape in. Mayank looks to defend but the ball takes the outside edge and goes between first slip and gully for a boundary. Would have been interesting to see if it would have carried to second slip if that was there.
Outside off, Mayank does not disturb it.
Length delivery on the pads, Mayank glances it towards mid-wicket and shouts a loud no to his partner.
Bouncer! A well directed one too. It is closer to the body. Agarwal though gets under it.
On the stumps, Virat lunges forward and blocks it to get through the over.
This time Kohli gets right behind the ball and keeps it down.
Beauty! Tossed up outside off, Kohli gets on his front foot to defend this but it turns away just a bit. Enough to beat the outside edge of Kohli's willow.
Floated on middle and leg, Kohli starts his innings with a solid front foot defense.
Short around off, Agarwal punches it towards cover and gets a single.
Short outside off, Mayank cuts it to the man at point.
Out walks the Indian skipper, Virat Kohli to a huge reception from the crowd. This is his 50th match as Test captain and he will be looking to make a mark on this game.

OUT! CAUGHT! A wicket right near the end of the second session of play and just what the doctor ordered for South Africa! Rabada is the man again to give the visitors a breakthrough. Bowls it on a length just outside off, it nips back in. Pujara is stuck in his crease and on the back foot. He tries to defend it but the ball goes off the outside edge low towards the left of first slip. Faf du Plessis, the South African skipper there makes no mistake there as he takes a very difficult catch. He is down on the ground after taking the catch almost in relief. A very important breakthrough for the Proteas as they break the 138-run stand.
FOUR! Punched with ease! Back of a length ball on off, Pujara just stands tall and punches this off his toes towards the point region for a boundary.
On the pads again, full ball. Pujara flicks this one towards mid-wicket again and takes a couple. That has been a very busy zone in Pujara's innings.
Full one on off, Pujara looks to defend but it comes off the inside half of the bat and goes on to hit the pads.
On the pads, Mayank flicks it towards mid-wicket and takes a single.
Full delivery on middle, pushed back towards Rabada.
On the stumps, Pujara comes down the track and keeps it out.

FOUR! Pujara gets to his fifty in style. Short around off, Pujara gets on his back foot and cuts it with grace through point for a boundary. Back-to-back fifties for Cheteshwar. He raises his bat as the crowd applaud his knock. He was dropped on 0 and he has made full use of it.
Follows it up with a calm front foot defense.

FOUR! Excellent use of the feet. Floated on middle, Pujara comes down the track, gets to the pitch of the ball and whips it between mid-wicket and mid on for a boundary. 150 up for India with this boundary.
Tossed up on off, Pujara blocks it.
Flighted on off, Pujara looks to defend but it goes off the inner half of his bat towards square leg.
Full around off, Mayank strokes it wide of sweeper cover for a couple.
Full on middle, Agarwal pushes it to mid on.
Full on off, MA pushes it to cover.
Length delivery around off, Mayank square drives it to point.
Good length ball on off, Agarwal blocks it.
Starts with a good length ball around off, Mayank keeps it out.
Kagiso Rabada is back into the attack now. 10-1-26-1 so far from him.
Sharp turn. Flighted on off, Pujara looks to defend but the ball spins away off the deck missing the outside edge and the off pole by only a fraction.
The batsman has punched the ball off the back foot.
Short around off, Mayank cuts it towards point and gets to the other end.
Floated on off and middle, Mayank comes down the track and looks to hit it straight down the ground but it comes off the lower half of his bat and goes straight to Keshav.
Short around off, Agarwal guides it down to short third man.
On the pads, Mayank looks to defend but gets hit on the pads.
Flighted on off, Mayank milks it to long off and keeps the strike.
On the stumps, Agarwal blocks it away.
FOUR! Poor ball. Drag down on the pads, Agarwal pulls it with ease through mid-wicket to fetch himself another boundary.
The batsman flicks it away with a wristy shot.
Once again it is short on off, Mayank taps it to point.
Short on middle, Agarwal pushes it back to the bowler.
Normalcy restored as this tossed up ball is kept out by CP.
Turn and bounce. Short outside off, Pujara gets on his back foot to punch it through the off side but the ball spins away and Cheteshwar after looking at that retracts  from the shot.
Gives it air on middle, Che glances it to mid-wicket.
Tossed up on middle and leg, Pujara glances it towards square leg and looks for one but Mayank sends him back.
Floated on middle, Cheteshwar keeps it out.
On the pads, Pujara turns it to square leg.
Once again short, this time Pujara cuts it towards point and keeps the strike.
SIX! A very impressive ball is followed by a sub-par delivery. Short on middle and leg, Pujara gets on his back foot and whacks it over the mid-wicket fence for the first maximum of the game.

Excellent ball. Muthusamy bowls it slower on off and middle. Pujara looks to defend but the ball grips and turns away beating the outside edge of Cheteshwar's  willow. First ball that has actually spun today.
Floated on middle, Pujara blocks it away.
A very good start is followed by a drag down. Short outside off, Mayank punches it to deep cover for one. Senuran is lucky that it is just a one.
Starts with a floated ball on off, Agarwal defends it off the front foot.
Bowling change. Senuran Muthusamy is finally introduced into the attack.
On the stumps, Puji defends it off the front foot.
Floated on off, Agarwal strokes it towards cover for a run.
On the stumps, Agarwal keeps it out.

Misfield and they get a quick single. Short on off, Pujara guides it towards point. Rabada misfields and they set off for a quick single. De Bruyn gets to the ball and sends an ordinary throw at the keeper's end. Quinton looks to flick it onto the stumps but misses.
Tossed up on middle, Pujara flicks it to the man at mid-wicket.
Floated on off, Pujara defends it off the front foot.
On the pads, Pujara tucks it fine down the leg side and keeps the strike.
Good length ball around off, Pujara looks to play it on the off side but it goes back to the bowler off the edge of his bat.
Once again short, Mayank this time pulls it just wide of mid-wicket for one.

FOUR! Pulled with power, aggression and control. Short ball on off, Mayank transfers his weight onto his back foot and pulls it through mid-wicket for a boundary. Brings up the 100-run stand in style.
On the pads, Agarwal flicks it to square leg.

FOUR! One trick too many maybe. Another short ball, Mayank gets on his back foot and hooks it through backward square leg for a boundary. He was not in complete control of that but he won't mind it. Partnership now moves to 99 with that.

FOUR! He was looking to pierce the gap on the leg side and after finding the fielder on the previous two occasions, he has finally managed to get it. On the pads, Pujara comes down the track and whips it behind square on the leg side to get a boundary.
On middle, Pujara comes down the track and whips it to mid-wicket.
On off, Pujara keeps it out.
Floated on off, Pujara comes down the track and whips it but finds square leg.
Tossed up on off, Cheteshwar defends it to the on side.
Floated on off, Pujara keeps it out.
Another short one. Mayank once again goes under the ball.
Comes around the wicket to Agarwal and bangs it in short. Agarwal ducks under it.
Good length delivery on off, Pujara nudges it towards point and gets one.
Back of a length on the body, Che tucks it towards square leg.
Hits the deck hard on off, Pujara comfortably taps it back to the bowler.
Bouncer around off, Pujara sways away from it.

Drinks Break! India continue to dominate. Mayank Agarwal and Cheteshwar Pujara have continued to dominate the South African bowling. The duo is looking strong and comfortable out in the middle. The former has reached his 50 and would like to convert this into a big one. Faf du Plessis needs wickets here and his bowlers are unable to find them. Can they find any source of inspiration after the break?
Once again drives it straight to the man at extra cover.
Floated on off, Mayank drives it straight to the man at catching position at short extra cover.
This one bounces off the surface. It is on off, Mayank defends it off the upper half of his bat.
Once again slightly short, Mayank tucks it to the right of short leg.
Shorter on off and middle, Mayank guides it towards point with a flat bat.
Floated on off, Mayank keeps it out.
The batsman defends it from within the crease.
On the pads, Agarwal flicks this one down the leg side for a single.
Bouncer outside off, Agarwal leaves it alone.

FOUR! Bouncer again but this time Agarwal does not shy away! Down the leg side, Agarwal gets on top of the bounce and rolls his wrists as he hooks this one all along the ground towards the fine leg boundary. However, this is a risky shot as there is a leg gully and a deep fine leg in place and the South African players are trying to lure Agarwal into that shot.
Bouncer down the leg side, Agarwal gets under it.
On the pads, Agarwal flicks it towards the leg side.
Full and floated outside off, Agarwal pushes this one towards long off for a single.
Defended off the front foot by the batsman presenting the full face of the bat.
On the pads again, flicked towards mid on for a single.
Fuller on the pads, pushed towards mid on.
Another one, a touch short, Agarwal cuts it towards cover-point and takes a single.
Short of a length outside off, Agarwal drives it towards point for a couple.
Pujara works it down the leg side.

A mix up again but luckily no harm done! Shorter delivery outside off, Pujara cuts this one towards cover-point. The man there runs after it and mops it up. There is a chance for the third but Pujara is not interested with Agarwal halfway down the track. However, the throw is at the keeper's end and that allows Agarwal to get back in as de Kock has a shy at the bowler's end. The bowler fails to collect the ball and the ball rolls towards mid on. Now Pujara wants a run but Mayank refuses. These two need to sort things out in their running.
Length ball on middle and off, Pujara defends it from within the crease.
Length ball on middle and leg, Pujara pushes it towards short mid on off the back foot.
Bouncer down the leg side, Pujara ducks under it.
Nortje still bowling quick, at 141.2 kph. Agarwal flicks it towards square leg and takes a single.
On the pads, pushed towards the man at mid on.
Shortish outside off, cut towards cover-point for a single.
Flatter on off, pushed towards the bowler again.
Tossed up on the fourth stump line, pushes it back to the bowler.
Floated outside off, pushed to the man at short cover.
Tossed up outside off, pushed towards the off side.
On the body, Pujara tucks it towards square leg. Maiden for Nortje to start off his new spell.
Another short one. This is outside off, Pujara sways away from it.
Back of a length ball on middle, Pujara tucks it to backward square leg.
Full on off, Cheteshwar defends it.
Another short one. Once again Pujara sits under it. This is further down the leg side. Anrich needs to correct his line if he wants to trouble the batter with these short stuff.
Bouncer! Nortje starts his new spell with the effort ball. It is around the body but down the leg side. Cheteshwar ducks under it.
Anrich Nortje is back on. 5-1-27-0 so far from him. He has been a touch expensive but bowled quick deliveries throughout his last spell.
On the stumps, kept out by MA.
Follows it up with a very calm front foot defense.

FIFTY FOR MAYANK AGARWAL! He continues his impressive run in Tests. Short around off, Mayank slams it through point for a boundary. He raises his bat as the crowd and his teammates applaud his knock. Agarwal will now look to convert this into a hundred. Brings up the 100 for India too.
Gives this one air on off, Agarwal blocks it.
Bounce on this one. It is short on off, it shoots up. Mayank defends it off the upper half of his bat towards point.
Flighted on off, Mayank keeps it out.
Length delivery on off, Pujara keeps it out to get through the over.
Ohh! Full on middle, Mayank looks to defend but the ball nips in. It takes the inside edge of his bat and goes behind square on the leg side for a single.
Good length ball on middle and leg, Mayank defends it late to the off side.
Full on off, Mayank drives it but cannot get it past the fielder at cover as the man there dives to his right and saves runs for his side.
Good length ball on the stumps, Mayank defends it off the back foot.
Full on off, Agarwal pushes it towards mid off.
FOUR! Cut and cut in typical Pujara style. Short on middle and off, Pujara gets on his back foot and cuts it late through backward point for a boundary.

What happened there? Flighted on off, Agarwal strokes it towards mid-wicket and looks for a single. Pujara is also in agreement but the bowler blocks him while he looks to take off. Luckily he manages to find a way and get to the other end without any casualty.
Beaten! Shorter outside off, Agarwal gets down on one knee and looks to play the late cut. The ball once again misses the outside edge of the bat by just a whisker.
Beauty! This one is floated around off, it spins and grips away after pitching. Agarwal looks to defend but misses. That was not too far away from the outside edge.
Floated on middle and leg, Mayank defends it to the on side.
Drag down outside off as he sees Mayank come down the track. Agarwal still manages to punch it towards cover.
Full and swinging away. Pujara pushes it with the swing towards mid off.
Once again full and close to off, Pujara defends it to the on side.
Full around off, Cheteshwar pushes it to mid on.
Continues to bowl in the channel outside off, Pujara is in no mood to disturb that.
Full outside off, Pujara shoulders arms to it.
Full around off, Pujara looks to defend it. It goes towards mid on off the inner half of his bat.
Loopy ball outside off, Agarwal leaves it alone.

A tiring day for the Indian bowlers. Till the first hour of the second session, the Indian bowlers were on top and enjoying themselves out in the middle. But after that their pain started. They had scalped 5 wickets in the first 44 overs of the day but for the next 2 to arrive they had to bowl almost the same. The duo of Jadeja and Ashwin had a long day in the field as they were made to bowl long spells. Ashwin managed to get rid of the tail at the fag end of the day, finishing with a 4-fer. Ishant Sharma was the only genuine bowler who went wicketless. Jadeja, Shami and Umesh Yadav had 1, 2 and 3 wickets respectively.

But just like every underdog story there was a fight. There was determination. The inspiration came from an unlikely source. Keshav Maharaj who was battling a shoulder injury joined hands with Vernon Philander who grabbed a pair in the first Test. The duo showed how to play in these testing conditions. They fought hard, battled the spinner and added 109. In a game where South Africa were trailing by 439 with just 2 wickets in hand. Their 109-run stand might not seem too much of a difference maker but the duo spent more than 3 hours out in the middle. In the process Maharaj got to his maiden Test fifty. The time spent by the duo made sure that even though India could enforce the follow-on they will have to wait till Day 4.

The day began as many people predicted it to begin.  South Africa lost night watchman Anrich Nortje early in the day. Theunis de Bruyn got a start but could not make the most of it. Then started the vistors' fight. First skipper Faf du Plessis and de Kock added a 75-run stand with the skipper getting to his fifty in the process. De Kock though could not continue his fight and Muthusamy too did not last long. Faf du Plessis also threw in his towel as he was dismissed by Ashwin. At 162/8 and just one hour of the second session gone, the question in everyone's mind was what will happen? Will India bat again today or will South Africa bat twice in a day?
Take a bow, Maharaj and Philander! When many expected and thought South Africa would not just bat twice but lose some wickets as well in their second innings, the duo had other ideas.

This is the 50th Test wicket for Ravichandran Ashwin against South Africa. That will be the last ball of the day as the umpire takes the bails off. STUMPS, DAY 3!

SAFE! Nothing on the Ultra Edge and India lose one of their 2 reviews. Flighted outside off, Rabada looks to drive but the ball spins in and goes to the keeper. Saha fumbles but then takes the catch. Jadeja and Saha put in an appeal. The convince Kohli to take it upstairs. The Indian skipper obliges. Replay roll in and it shows nothing on the Ultra Edge.
Review time! Virat Kohli has signalled the 'T' in a cheeky manner. Looks like there is nothing there but on the advice of Saha his skipper does take the review.
Flighted on off, Philander defends it with soft hands towards cover and gets to the other end.

Beauty from Jadeja. Tossed up around off, Philander looks to defend but the ball turns away and squares him up.
Flighted on off, Philander defends it off the front foot.

Full and floated on middle, Philander looks to defend but fails to do so. The Indian players put in an appeal but nothing from the umpire. The ball goes towards silly point. Replays roll in and show that the ball had taken an inside way before thudding onto the pads and going towards silly point.
The batsman has played that off the front foot and into the ground.
On middle and leg, Rabada just manages to get his bat on it. He flicks it down the leg side, fine. The fielder in the deep mops it up and the batters take two.

Kagiso Rabada is the last man in. 8th wicket fell more than 3 hours earlier, Rabada would have thought he would come earlier but here he is, coming out to bat at the toe end of the day to bat for the first time.

OUT! CAUGHT! Finally the resistance of South Africa is broken and Ashwin is the man to provide the breakthrough! Ashwin bowls a floated one on the pads, Maharaj looks to flick it down the leg side. He connects but does so uppishly. The leg slip fielder is perfectly positioned and takes the catch there. Rohit Sharma takes a dolly and he is getting hugs from all his teammates. A brilliant, gritty and fighting knock from Keshav Maharaj comes to an end.
The batsman has defended it by getting right behind the line of the delivery.
Maharaj prods forward and looks to defend this one. The ball comes off the inside edge and hits the batsman on the pads. India put in a stifled appeal but nothing from the umpire.
Maharaj goes back in his crease and blocks this one out.
The batsman has played that off the front foot and into the ground.
Maharaj drives this one through mid off and takes a single.
Floated on middle and off, pushed towards mid off.
Maharaj prods forward and defends this one.
Second slip in now. Mayank Agarwal goes from short leg to second slip and he is on his knees.
EDGED AND FOUR! Fortune favours the brave and that is what is happening here. Shortish outside off, Maharaj edges this one. The ball flies wide of first slip and into the third man fence.
Maharaj watchfully defends this one out.
Philander defends this one onto the pitch.
The batsman has defended it by getting right behind the line of the delivery.
Philander looks to defend but the ball goes off the inside edge onto the pads towards the leg side.
Philander defends this one onto the pitch.
Philander drives this one towards mid on but straight to the man.
Philander goes back in his crease and defend it towards the leg side.
Ravichandran Ashwin is back. 25-8-66-2, his figures so far.
Maharaj pushes this one towards the mid off region.
Keshav goes deep in his crease again to block it out.
Maharaj goes deep into his crease and blocks this one out.
The batsman has defended it by getting right behind the line of the delivery.

Close one! Good awareness by Maharaj! He goes back in his crease, defends it off the back foot. The ball bounces inside the crease and is going onto the stumps. Maharaj knows exactly where the ball is and just pushes it away with his bat behind the keeper.
Floated on middle and off, Maharaj pushes it back towards the bowler.
The batsman has played that off the front foot and into the ground.
Length ball outside off, pushed towards point.
Another bouncer, Philander does well to evade it.
Bouncer on middle and off, Philander sways away from it.
Down the leg side, Philander looks to flick it but misses.
FOUR! Gorgeous drive! Full and outside off, Philander just leans into the drive and creams this one through the cover region. Nothing like a tailender this.
The batsman has punched that ball through the offside.

FOUR! 100-run stand up between Maharaj and Philander! Two warriors from South Africa have stood up and frustrated India. Another short ball outside off, this time Maharaj connects well and the ball races to the point boundary. They have given some joy to the Proteas fans. This is the highest 9th wicket stand for South Africa against India.
EDGED AND FOUR! Shortish delivery outside off, Maharaj has a slash at it but the ball goes off the outside edge into the third man fence.
Maharaj gets onto the front foot and defends it onto the pitch.
Outside off, left alone by Maharaj.
Darted on the off pole, Maharaj blocks it out.
Ravindra Jadeja is back. 31-13-67-1, his figures so far.
Full delivery outside off, pushed towards the man at extra-cover.
Philander comes onto the front foot and blocks it out again.
Another good length ball outside off, pushed towards the man at cover-point.
Good length ball outside off, pushed towards point.
On the pads, Maharaj flicks it fine towards the leg side and takes a single.
Good length ball on middle and off, blocked out.

Philander gets another inside edge onto the pads. Does well to negotiate the over.
Pitched way wide outside off, Philander leaves it alone.
Philander defends this one off the back foot.
Philander looks to drive at this one but the ball goes off the inside edge onto the pads. It lobs towards Ashwin but falls well short of him.

Floats one outside off, Philander misses his defense and is hit on the pads.
On the pads of Maharaj, he flicks this one towards square leg for a couple.
Maharaj defends it by getting right behind the line of the delivery.
Defended off the back foot by the batsman.
Maharaj defends this one off the back foot.
On the pads, Maharaj flicks it towards the leg side.
Maharaj mistimes his lofted shot over mid on. The ball luckily for him clears the fielder in the circle there and the batters are able to take one.

Plays a square cut. The ball goes towards the point region and the batters take one.
Maharaj pushes this one towards gully and takes a quick single.
The batsman has defended it by getting right behind the line of the delivery.

This time a better appeal! Floated outside off, spinning in. Maharaj looks to block but misses. He is hit on the pad. The Indians appeal but the umpire is unmoved. The replays show that the impact is outside off.
Short and wide outside off, Maharaj cuts this towards backward point and Pujara gives it the chase. Keeps the ball in play and the batters take two.
Floated on middle and leg, pushed towards mid on.
The batsman has defended it by getting right behind the line of the delivery.
Desperation for the Indians and now it is showing. Floated on off, Philander blocks it out. The Indians put in a stifled appeal but the umpire is unmoved. Replays show no pad involved.
Outside off, watchfully defended.

Darted on the off pole, pushed back towards the bowler.

DRINKS! Well, a very rare occasion where we can say that South Africa have have gained some foothold in the game. They have frustrated the Indian bowlers and the pair of Maharaj and Philander have tired them out. They have formed a 82-run stand and India will now be thinking that they might have to bowl on Day 4 as well. With this pair going strong and Rabada still to come, South Africa have turned the match on its head.
Tossed up on off, Keshav looks to defend but gets an inside edge onto the pads.
Maharaj gets back in his zone and defends it solidly.

FIFTY FOR MAHARAJ! Champion stuff from him. Yes we have seen brilliant knock from the Indian batters but this innings cannot be looked past just like that. He was nursing a shoulder injury but he has fought it out in the middle like a warrior. Tossed up ball on middle, Keshav glances it towards cow corner and calls for two straight away. Philander responds, taking Maharaj to his maiden Test fifty. He raises his bat as his family, teammates and the crowd applauds his courageous fight.
Now Maharaj calmly blocks this ball.
FOUR! Maharaj gets to his best Test score in style. Shorter on off, Maharaj punches it through cover-point for a boundary.
DROPPED! Tough chance but could have been taken! Floated on middle, Maharaj punches it uppishly to the right of Ashwin. He dives to that side and gets his hand to the ball but cannot bask it in.
Tossed up on the stumps, Vernon defends it off the front foot.
On middle and off, Philander looks to defend but gets an inside edge onto the pads.
Defended off the front foot by the batsman presenting the full face of the bat.
Spin and bounce. Flighted around off, Philander plants his front foot out and tries to defend it but the ball goes past the outside edge.
Shorter around off, Maharaj punches it to the off side and gets to the other end.
Philander defends it off the front foot with soft hands towards cover and gets a single.
Floated on off, Maharaj defends it onto the ground.
FOUR! Creamed away. Tossed up on off, Maharaj smashes it through mid off for a boundary.
On the pads, Maharaj flicks it to square leg.
Floated on off, Philander looks to defend but it goes off the edge wide of slip for a single.
Slightly quicker on middle and off, Maharaj strokes it through cover a single. This one kept a bit low.
Tossed up on off, Maharaj keeps it out.
Ravichandran Ashwin is back.
On the stumps, Philander defends it off the front foot.

Ravindra Jadeja is into the attack once more. 27-11-61-1 so far from him.
FOUR! Educational edge!  Good length ball on off, Maharaj looks to defend but it goes off the edge through the vacant gully region for a boundary.

A better release might have put Philandeer in trouble. Fuller on middle and off, Vernon pushes it to the left of mid on and scampers through for a single. Umesh yadav there gets to the ball quickly but cannot release it proeprly allowing Philander to get back in with ease.
Good length delivery on off, Philander defends it towards cover and shouts a loud no.
Fuller ball on middle and leg, Maharaj nudges it to the on side and gets to the other end.
Length ball on off, Maharaj defends it with a dead-bat.
Very full on middle and leg. Keshav defends it towards mid off. The length of the ball created some excitement in the cubical.
On the fourth stump line, Vernon leaves it alone.
Good length ball on off, Philander defends it to the off side.
Bouncer again. This one is to Philander. Vernon sways away from it.
Length ball on off, KM defends it towards cover and takes a single. He is feeling his right shoulder as the ball jarred his bat.
Bouncer! Maharaj ducks under it.
Ouch that must have hurt. Back of a length ball around the body, Maharaj hops and does well to keep it down. Even though it hit his glove it went wide of short leg.
Good length ball around off, the ball swings in after pitching. Philander does well to defend it off the outer half of his bat.
Fuller on off, VP defends it off the front foot.
Fuller on off, Vernon pushes it to cover.
Outside off, Philander leaves it alone.
Azharuddin-esque fielding from Ishant. Back of a length ball around the body, Maharaj defends it and calls for a single. Ishant gets to the ball quickly and does a no look throw.

A slight halt in play. Ishant Sharma thinks that the ball has gone out of shape a bit and wants to get it checked. The umpire removes the 8-shaped gauge, passes the ball through it and gives the ball back to Ishant informing him that the ball is fine and he should continue.

Direct hit and that could have been trouble. Fuller around off, Philander pushes it towards cover and calls for a quick single. The fielder has a shy at the keeper's end but misses. Saha fails to gather it too but that does not cost any extra run.
Back of a length ball on off, Maharaj defends it to get through the over.
Wild from Maharaj. Good length ball outside off, Keshav swings his bat at it but misses.
Back of a length ball on off, Maharaj keeps it out.
The floodlights in the stadium have been turned on.
Bouncer! Maharaj ducks under it.

Play and a miss. Length delivery on top of off, Maharaj looks to pull but the ball does not rise as much as he expected and he misses it. Mayank Agarwal standing in the close-in position chirps a loud 'aye'.

This is what a hard ball does. Good length ball on off, the ball shoots off the surface. It hits the upper half of Philander's bat and flies uppishly towards the long leg fielder where he takes it on the bounce. The batters take a single.

FOUR LEG BYES! Ishant bowls another one down the leg side, Maharaj looks to flick but it goes off his pad fine down the leg side. It is wide of Saha who was diving to his left and races away to the fence.
Good length ball on off, Keshav looks to defend but gets an inside edge onto the pads.
Bouncer! A wayward one though as this one is down the leg side.
Ishant sprays one down the leg side. Maharaj looks to flick but misses.
Good length ball around off, Maharaj drives it on the up to mid off.

Ishant starts his new spell with a fuller ball outside off. Maharaj initially looks to play but then changes his mind. Too late though as the ball hits the inside edge of the bat. It bounces away from the off stump and goes to the keeper.
Ishant Sharma to bowl from the other end with the new ball. 7-0-28-0 so far for him.
FOUR! This will give Philander more confidence to play against the new ball. Slightly fuller around off, Vernon drives it through point for a boundary.
Length delivery outside off, Philander leaves it late.
Another good ball. Length ball on off and middle, Philanderr looks to defend but does so off the outer half of his bat as the ball zips away.
Length delivery on middle and leg, Vernon looks to defend but misses and gets hit high on the pad. The new, hard ball seems to be intimidating him.
Good leave! Length delivery outside off. It is an inswinger but Philander is aware of his off stump and leaves it alone. The ball was not far away from the stump though.
Good length ball pitching on off, it comes in with the angle. Philander looks to defend but he does so off the upper half of his bat.
Second new ball has now been taken. Mohammed Shami to use it first up. Three slips and a gully for him.
Maharaj lunges forward and blocks this tossed up ball to get through the over.

Outside off, Maharaj leaves it alone.
Defended off the front foot by the batsman presenting the full face of the bat.

FOUR! The ball is following Ishant everywhere. Short around off, Maharaj gets on his back foot and cuts it nicely through point. Ishant goes behind it from backward point but he knew he was always going to come second so he withdraws. Pujara from cover goes and brings the ball back from the fence.
Second new ball is due now. However, India have opted against taking it.
FOUR! Good ball but wonderfully played. Full and it zips in off the deck. Philander drives it sweetly wide of Ishant Sharma at mid on for a boundary.
Full on off, Vernon defends it by bending his back.

Floated on middle and leg, Philander pushes it to mid off for one.
Ravindra Jadeja to bowl from the other end. 2 overs left for the second new ball.
First over after Tea well negotiated by Maharaj. He blocks this length ball on the off pole line back towards the bowler.

Good length ball outside off, pushed towards cover.
Goes for the shorter one this time, down the leg side. Maharaj ducks under it.

The Indian players are back out on the field and are in a huddle. They are followed by the South African batters, Vernon Philander and Keshav Maharaj with the latter being on strike. He is carrying a slight niggle in his right shoulder and India might be looking to take advantage of it. Mohammed Shami to continue the proceedings with the ball.
... Day 3, Evening session ...

A comparatively frustrating session for the Indian bowlers. They did not concede too many runs but would be frustrated not to wrap up the tail. They came close but for a change the rub of the green went the other way. India would now hope that the Tea break brings in a lapse of concentration and they can end the innings quickly. South Africa, on the other hand, would hope that Maharaj and Philander continue to be a thorn for the hosts. What will happen? Join us after the break to find out.

India got rid of Muthusamy and Faf du Plessis in the first hour of the session. The latter played really well before his departure and when he fell it looked like South Africa would bundle out under 200 but Maharaj and Philander fought it out and made sure they frustrated the Indian bowlers, in the process ensuring that South Africa had no more casualties heading into Tea.

Commendable performance from Keshav Maharaj and Vernon Philander. Forget about batting through the session, it felt like South Africa would bat twice in this session but Philander and Maharaj had other ideas.
Flatter on middle and off, Philander looks to defend but gets an inside edge onto the pads. THAT WILL BE TEA ON DAY 3!

Shami straightaway looks to attack the stumps after that halt in play but Maharaj is solid in his defense.

The physio is out now to have a look at Keshav Maharaj. He incurred a shoulder injury yesterday and that pull seems to be causing him some discomfort. The cause of that injury was when he was trying to field he fell awkwardly, injuring his right shoulder in the process.

OUT! LBW! Brilliant decision from umpire Nigel Llong! India strike very soon after the break. Floated delivery outside off, Jadeja was aiming for the rough. We are back for the second session. The Indian players are out in the field. Senuran Muthusamy and skipper Faf du Plessis walk out to the middle to resume their innings. Ravindra Jadeja to bowl the first over post Lunch.
... Day 3, Afternoon Session ...

So even after managing to score 100 runs in the session, they trail by a massive 465 runs and Faf du Plessis will now have to bat out of his skin with the tail if his side want to get some respectable total and gain some confidence. Can the Protea skipper do it or will India continue to steamroll the visitors? Join us for the 2nd Session to find out.

The day started on a positive note for India as Shami got rid of nightwatchman, Anrich Nortje. Theunis de Bruyn was looking good and got off to a start but failed to convert it as Umesh Yadav sent him back to the pavilion. Skipper Faf du Plessis and wicket-keeper batsman, Quinton de Kock then put up a fight. The duo counter-attacked the Indian bowlers and took charge of the situation. They added 75 runs, with the skipper getting to his fifty before Ashwin's gem got the better of de Kock. Muthusamy then joined his skipper and they managed to see through the session.
Another session that had India's name written all over it. 7 sessions and all have been won by India. That shows how far ahead the hosts are in this game.

Jaffa by Ashwin to end the session. Gives this one a lot of air, Muthusamy looks to defend this one off the front foot but the ball pitches and turns away sharply beating the outside edge of Muthusamy's blade. Oohs and Aahs all around but Muthusamy survives. LUNCH ON DAY 3!

OUT! TIMBER! What a beauty by Ravichandran Ashwin! De Kock cannot believe he has been bowled and is still having a look at the stumps. His skipper asks him from the other end whether he nicked it to which de Kock denies. De Kock then asks one of the Indian players and he replies that de Kock has been bowled. He looks at the giant screen and then starts walking back to the pavilion. South Africa 6 down now and du Plessis looks like the lone warrior now.

He was amazing yesterday with the ball.

PITCH REPORT - Murali Kartik and Sunil Gavaskar are the pitch analyst for the day. Gavaskar says that there is rough for Jadeja outside the off stump of the left-hander and there will be odd balls that will turn but Gavaskar thinks that the visitors should not worry much as it is still a good wicket to bat on. Sunil thinks there is no devil in the pitch and South Africa need to fight the devil that is just in their head. Kartik tells the texture of the surface is hard. Sunil then adds that the spinner will come into play but tells it is not a crumbly wicket and it is still good to bat on. Kartik adds that there is grass on the middle of the pitch which will help the pacer and some of the balls from there have kept low. He asks Gavaskar on how should one face such deliveries, Gavaskar jokes and says that the batsman can just pray.

Welcome to the Day 3 of the Freedom Trophy. India are well and truly on top of this one. India managed to get 3 wickets towards the end of Day 2. Kohli would be hoping that his boys continue their good work today as well. The question is if India restrict the visitors under 300 will they give the follow-on? As for the visitors, if they manage to avoid the follow-on score then that would be a morale booster for them. Can South Africa put on a fight or will India continue their dominance.
... Day 3, Morning Session ...

So, what is in store for us on Day 3? Will South Africa collapse meekly or will they put up a resistance similar to the one they put up at Vizag in the first innings? Join us tomorrow at 0930 Local (0400 GMT) to find out. Till then, Adios and take care!

Harsha Bhogle is having a chat with Ajinkya Rahane. Rahane says that the way they batted they thought they have super-fast bowlers and hence they wanted to play the one hour well. Admits that they were looking at 500-plus but the way Jadeja and Kohli batted made it look easy. Rahane feels that this is not a 600 wicket. On batting with Kohli, Rahane says they enjoy each other's company and they knew they were one batsman short and needed to build a partnership. On the conditions, Rahane says it is better than Vizag as it was very hot and humid there. On whether the game will be spin dominated, Rahane tells it is hot and there is moisture in the wicket, so the pacers can exploit that. As far as spin is concerned, Jinx says the ball is turning and  feels Ashwin and Jadeja are world-class bowlers, calling them dangerous on every wicket.

South Africa came into bat later in the third session and their top order was dismantled by the Indian bowling attack. Umesh Yadav took 2 wickets while Mohammed Shami also bagged one as they made full use of the new ball. Markram, Elgar and Bavuma were the victims who were dismissed in single digits as the quality of the Indian bowling attack was too much for them.

Earlier in the day, India cruised along as they posted a mammoth total of 601 runs on the board with three 100-plus run stands in the innings. The star of the day was King Virat Kohli who scored a double ton and formed century stands with Rahane and Jadeja respectively. Rahane scored a half ton and so did Jadeja, but one must say that had Jadeja been a bit selfish, he would have got to his ton as well. He fell for 91 trying to hit quick runs for his side. Kohli was unbeaten at the other end and declared the innings as soon as Jadeja departed with Kohli scoring 254 runs. South Africa were toothless in their bowling and not one bowler stood out. Rabada took 3 wickets while Maharaj and Muthusamy had one each. They leaked runs however and the wickets that fell were too late.

So, India walk back to the pavilion led by their skipper Virat Kohli amongst huge applause from the crowd. South Africa lost three wickets later in the evening but the night watchman has done his job as the visitors finish Day 2 on 36/3.

India have won the series and engraved their name in the history books as this becomes their 11th consecutive Test series win at home. This is not the end of the series though. Indian skipper, Virat Kohli, who is also the Man of the Match comes in for a chat. Talking about his seventh double ton, Kohli says that captaincy responsibility has helped him. Adds that he does not plan to go and score a double century but goes in with the mindset of playing five sessions for the team and score runs. On his muted celebrations after reaching the milestone, Kohli says that he has matured over the years which is a natural process. Adds that he is in a phase of his career where things like scoring centuries or double centuries does not matter much to him. Points out that helping the team win is more important. On his stand with Rahane, when Rabada was bowling well on Day 2 morning, Kohli says that he enjoys batting with Rahane. Points out that both of them love to play against top-class bowlers and score runs for the side. Adds that they both help each other whenever they are out in the middle. Talking about the catching in the slip cordon, Kohli points that they have planned well and everyone is doing well. Mentions Saha for his superb keeping and adds that even Ashwin came back into the side well. On the unassailable lead in the series, Kohli says that the series win is okay but mentions that since all these games are part of the ICC Test Championship, hence they will not take the foot off the gas.

Faf du Plessis, the South African skipper is the first one to have a word. Talking about the first innings, Faf says that the first innings are always important in the subcontinent. Congratulates Kohli for his superb double ton and points out that the side got tired up because of tough two days. Adds that the team needs to be on top of the game but they weren't and hence the defeat. Talking further on Kohli's century, Faf says that Kohli was too good in the entire innings. Says that Virat looked determined and he was hungry for runs. On his three pacer combination, Faf believes the selection was a right call but admits that apart from Philander and to some extent Rabada, none of the bowlers bowled well. Points out that the Indian seamers have done well and they never look out of form. Mentions that he can't blame debutant Nortje for this game. On Ngidi, Faf says that he is fine and working well on his fitness but on these conditions he needs to be completely fit to bowl longer spells.
Stay tuned for the presentation.

Umesh Yadav and Wriddhiman Saha are in for a quick chat with Sanjay Manjrekar. Talking about the two catches that Saha took off Umesh's bowling, the pacer thanks his wicket-keeper and says that with Saha, they're are sure that even if the ball is down the leg side, Saha can catch them. Talking about his second ball wicket, Umesh points out that there is a healthy competition in the team. Adds that he keeps working hard and practices well. Points that he has a mindset that whenever he gets an opportunity, he is ready to do well. Saha talking about his keeping says that keeping against the pacers is tough as they bowl with the wobbly seam and they practice as per the conditions. On his fitness, Saha says that everyone works well with the trainer and they prepare well ahead of the games. On his return to the side, Umesh says that he knew that he will get a game for sure and adds that he had taken 10 wickets in his last game in India and was very confident.

India dominated the game from the moment the toss went in their favour. The hosts after opting to bat put up a massive total of 601/5, courtesy of a magnificent unbeaten 254 from skipper Virat Kohli. With the help of a century from Mayank Agarwal and fifties from Jadeja, Pujara and Rahane, the Indians posted a huge first innings total. The hosts continued their dominance with the ball too as they wrapped up South Africa for 275. Ashwin was the star with the ball in the first innings as he finished with a 4-fer.

We were treated by another brilliant display of bowling by the Indian bowlers. All the recognized bowlers got into the wickets column. Jadeja and Umesh shared 6 wickets amongst themselves whereas Ashwin got two. While Shami and Ishant had one wicket each. The duo of Ashwin and Umesh had a very good game with the ball finishing the match with 6 wickets each.

It was a lacklustre show once again from the South African batters, especially the top order. When there is a follow-on, the top order, especially the openers need to put up a fight but it was a no show. Only 4 players got into the double digit score. With two of them, Maharaj and Philander being tail-enders. This in itself shows the sorry state of the South African batting. Elgar and Temba Bavuma were the only two 'recognized' batters who showed some fight. Faf du Plessis showed resilience but that was not good enough.

After keeping the suspense on Day 3, India decided to enforce the follow-on. They got off to a brilliant start, getting rid of Aiden Markram on the very second ball of the day. The Indian bowlers were well on top in the first session and picked 4 wickets. They had a similar start to the second session as well. They got 3 wickets post Lunch but Keshav Maharaj and Vernon Philander once again troubled the hosts. But the Tea break brought a lapse in concentration between the duo as it took only around 7 overs for India to wrap up the innings.

2-0 it is which means India have taken an unassailable lead in the three-match series. With another 40 points in the World Test Championship, India not just increase their lead at the top they also become the first team to reach 200 points and maintain their unbeaten run in WTC.

Welcome back for the second session of the day. The Indian players walk out to the middle. Temba Bavuma and Quinton de Kock comes out to the middle as well. Ravichandran Ashwin to bowl the first over after Lunch, de Kock to face. Two slips, a short leg and a silly point as the close-in catchers. Here we go...
... Day 4, Session 2 ...

So a South Africa defeat looks inevitable. Only a miracle can see them go past India's trail forget about putting India to bat. They will now look to play hour by hour. Kohli and his troops will now be looking to wrap this up in the next session itself. Can they do it? Join us for the second session to find out.

It was a brilliant bowling display from the Indians. They bowled the right lines and lengths and kept the Protea batters at bay. Ashwin's fine Test continued as he added 2 more wickets to his 4 that he took in the first innings of the game. Ishant and Umesh were the other bowlers to get into the wickets column. But the unsung hero of this session has to be Wriddhimann Saha. He took two blinders which are equally his wicket as the bowlers.

After enforcing the follow-on, India started the day with a bang. On the very second ball of the day, Ishant struck gold sending Markram for a duck, making him grab a pair for the first time in his Test career. Luck too went India's way as Ball Tracker later on showed that the ball was missing the stumps. That wicket though set the pretext of the session. Theunis de Bruyn stayed for a while before a stunning catch from Saha saw his back. Elgar and Faf du Plessis then tried to grind it out in the middle. The duo added a 49-run stand before the skipper was sent back after another fine catch from Saha. Elgar was fighting a lone battle but a rush of blood moment saw him throw his wicket away.
If we say it is India's session then that would mean we are just stating the obvious. India have completely annihilated South Africa in this session.
